Members of Pakistan's National Assembly are involved in the issue of democracy and dynasty 
under Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto, who they charge with trying to build a political dynasty by 
appointing family members to key government positions.  The Bhuttos has been out of power 
since Benazir's father, Prime Minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, was executed after a military coup in 
1977.

An American consultant to the assembly says there is a rebirth of democracy but "it remains in 
its infancy."  Western diplomats and Pakistani analysts see growing signs of corruption and 
patronage, and complain that Bhutto's government is obsessed with political gamesmanship.</SUM>

