SUMMARIZER="G">

The husband of ousted Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto, businessman Asif Ali Zardari, was 
arrested in Karachi for alleged involvement in extortion and illegal bank loans.  He has been a 
major target of investigations since Bhutto's dismissal for allegedly heading an administration 
riddled with corruption, nepotism and abuse of power.  Ms. Bhutto says the arrest is to intimidate 
and blackmail her.  She visited Zardari at a police interrogation center and later appeared before 
a special court in Lahore, where she faces charges of wrongdoing.

Both Bhutto and Zardari are running the October Assembly elections, but she could be barred if 
convicted.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d088"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT942-16751"
SELECTOR="D"
SUMMARIZER="G">

Nusrat Bhutto and her son Murtaza Bhutto are involved in a family feud with Benazir Bhutto, 
Pakistan's Prime Minister.  The feuding was triggered after police fired on demonstrators 
Wednesday attempting to march to the grave of former Prime Minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto to 
celebrate his 66th birthday.

Benazir removed her mother, Nusrat, as co-chair of the ruling Pakistan's People's Party.  
Murtaza faces charges of running an anti-government terrorism campaign during 16 years of 
self-imposed exile.  The feud erupted this week when Murtaza's supporters refused to let Benazir 
visit her father's grave unless he was released to preside over the celebration.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d088"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FBIS-53091"
SELECTOR="D"
SUMMARIZER="G">

The Pakistan People's Party (PPP) is not at its best.  There are embarrassing items of omission 
and commission and widespread skepticism about how confident a grip the Benazir Bhutto 
government has over the issues needing effective handling.

 What is undermining the PPP's administrative image is the family feud, which shows no sign of 
abating.  Ms. Bhutto is apparently trying damage limitation.  However, the real damage to the 
PPP is its own workers hurling thoughtless and undignified accusations at Nusrat Bhutto.  Ms. 
Bhutto should sort out family misunderstanding in private and clear the questions of 
"succession." The PPP is not Bhutto's family property.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d088"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FBIS3-40602"
SELECTOR="D"
SUMMARIZER="G">

Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto said the question of rolling back Pakistan's peaceful nuclear 
programs does not arise because the nation's defense depends upon it.  She also asked the United 
States to review its decision on the use of the Pressler Amendment, which stopped military and 
economic aid to Pakistan.

US and European nations objections to nuclear programs are limited to the Islamic world.  Soon 
after Benazir Bhutto's statement, Washington indicated that the amendment would end.  How 
did it suddenly become useless?  Benazir Bhutto should remove all doubts and skepticism about 
intentions to make an agreement with the US over the nuclear program.</SUM>

<SUM
